What other goals might appear that you've 
come across why people want to do this?

184
00:16:31,360 --> 00:16:36,240
Well, sometimes there's a legibility issue 
that is really glaring once you see it and  

185
00:16:36,240 --> 00:16:40,880
then people are too close in to notice it, 
so this is why it's like you have to show it  

186
00:16:40,880 --> 00:16:45,280
to a lot of people that aren't familiar with 
looking at those letter forms and stuff. The  

187
00:16:45,280 --> 00:16:49,520
one that came to mind immediately when you asked 
was when I did a refresh for Jeni's Ice Cream,  

188
00:16:49,520 --> 00:16:56,600
which is a really amazing ice cream brand based 
out of Columbus, Ohio. They had a few utilitarian  

189
00:16:56,600 --> 00:17:02,000
things in mind. They had this long J that created 
this pocket of white space underneath it that  

190
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,280
made it really hard to design with, but then 
the biggest glaring one was that they decided  

191
00:17:06,280 --> 00:17:14,680
to make the apostrophe of the Jeni's over the 
I as a cool thing. It made the word look like  

192
00:17:14,680 --> 00:17:21,480
it said penis because of the way that J was drawn.
It had a little loop at the top of the J. That was  

193
00:17:21,480 --> 00:17:27,120
the most specific fix that I've ever had to do, 
is make the logo not say penis anymore. But yeah,  

194
00:17:27,120 --> 00:17:33,120
I feel like a lot of it is misreads. When 
you think about logos and things like that,  

195
00:17:33,120 --> 00:17:39,120
you want it to be something that, at a super 
fast glance, people can read it right away.  

196
00:17:39,120 --> 00:17:42,560
That doesn't mean that everything has to be 
simple, but it just means that everything  

197
00:17:42,560 --> 00:17:46,640
has to be incredibly legible, especially when 
you're starting a new company or you have a  

198
00:17:46,640 --> 00:17:52,800
less recognizable brand. Because eventually, you 
become a household name and then people can look  

199
00:17:52,800 --> 00:17:59,000
at just the color and recognize that it's you or 
whatever, but it takes a long time building equity  

200
00:17:59,000 --> 00:18:04,800
before you get that. Until that, it's really 
important that the legibility is just super tight.

201
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:09,960
Let's talk about actually thinking 
through my new logo and brand. Can  

202
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:13,320
you just talk about what you had 
in mind as you started to explore  

203
00:18:13,320 --> 00:18:18,640
directions and we started narrowing what was 
the mindset, and the approach, and the vibe?

204
00:18:18,640 --> 00:18:25,400
I think with the Lenny's brand, you are what 
I would call a person that has a beloved fan  

205
00:18:25,400 --> 00:18:34,360
base that we don't want to exclude or offend by 
shifting gears super crazily. When I was looking  

206
00:18:34,360 --> 00:18:41,560
at redoing your brand, it was about what's here 
that we can look at that we should keep or at  

207
00:18:41,560 --> 00:18:47,640
least explore keeping in order to make sure that 
it still feels the same on the other side? We  

208
00:18:47,640 --> 00:18:52,960
didn't want to do anything super drastic. Some 
of the things to think about in that way are  

209
00:18:52,960 --> 00:18:57,120
you have this sort of handwritten approach to a 
lot of the parts of your brand, and I was like,  

210
00:18:57,120 --> 00:19:02,600
"How do we do something that feels handwritten, 
that feels like it could jive with the handwriting  

211
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:08,640
scripts and stuff that you were using but might 
feel a little bit more refined moving forward and  

212
00:19:08,640 --> 00:19:13,240
in a way that could blend with illustration so 
that the illustration and the letter forms all  

213
00:19:13,240 --> 00:19:19,920
feel like they were created by the same hand?"
A lot of times for me, when it comes to doing  

214
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:25,480
an exploration like that, it's about how do we 
make sure everything feels like it was created  

215
00:19:25,480 --> 00:19:31,440
at the same time and not that we just tacked on 
new things? Figuring out how to blend everything  

216
00:19:31,440 --> 00:19:36,720
together is important. Color was also a big 
one. I feel like people's color stories are  

217
00:19:36,720 --> 00:19:41,840
something that is an immediate read, where 
if you blur your eyes and look at a brand,  

218
00:19:41,840 --> 00:19:47,680
you can recognize it by its color, and so I 
think keeping your color similar was a big  

219
00:19:47,680 --> 00:19:54,160
one too. But then I really wanted to try different 
approaches with the typography, doing stuff that  

220
00:19:54,160 --> 00:19:59,920
was a little bit more clean, doing stuff that 
still had a bit of a funky edge to it. Because  

221
00:19:59,920 --> 00:20:07,280
your original Lenny's podcast type had this sort 
of cut papery, a little bit off kilter vibe to it,  

222
00:20:07,280 --> 00:20:12,280
and so trying to capture that but with new 
cleaner typography. That was really fun. 

223
00:20:13,880 --> 00:20:20,600
I was using a typeface Degular as part of it, 
which has a nice wonkiness to it. It was drawn  

224
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:25,760
by a friend of mine, James Edmondson, who I 
love all of his stuff. That was one of the  

225
00:20:25,760 --> 00:20:31,680
things that we approached because I felt like 
it could capture the look of the original cut  

226
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:37,320
paperesque type. But yeah, it was really fun to 
try a lot of different things and work within the  

227
00:20:37,320 --> 00:20:42,320
iconography that you had used on a few stuff 
with the microphones, and also marshmallows,  

228
00:20:42,320 --> 00:20:47,480
and campfires, and all kinds of things, and 
just trying to make a more unified system.

229
00:20:47,480 --> 00:20:51,440
Are there things that didn't work as you 
tried to explore this process that you recall,  

230
00:20:51,440 --> 00:20:53,200
that might be worth sharing of just like, "Oh,  

231
00:20:53,200 --> 00:20:57,560
that was a cool concept," but didn't 
quite work the way you thought?

232
00:20:57,560 --> 00:21:04,960
With working on this refresh, so much of it was 
thinking about what are the immediate uses of the  

233
00:21:04,960 --> 00:21:13,040
logo. Your logo, you have these very specific 
uses that you need it for, the avatar for the  

234
00:21:13,040 --> 00:21:19,680
podcast being a top one. Some people, they'll 
design a logo and then have these illustrative  

235
00:21:19,680 --> 00:21:23,920
versions of the logo that get rolled out for 
other things, but I feel like those layouts  

236
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:31,200
were actually more important than even just 
having a basic letterhead-esque logo. That's an  

237
00:21:31,200 --> 00:21:35,760
interesting way to approach it, because usually, 
it's like let's start simple, and expand, and make  

238
00:21:35,760 --> 00:21:41,880
it crazier. I felt like we had to always keep 
those things in play, so it was designing brand  

239
00:21:41,880 --> 00:21:50,560
assets while also designing the logo. Sometimes 
you'll see examples of that in early explorations  

240
00:21:50,560 --> 00:21:56,280
just because it makes it feel real to the client.
That's why there's always the tote bag. You got  

241
00:21:56,280 --> 00:22:00,720
to put the logo on the tote bag and then it feels 
real or whatever. But in our case, we had really  

242
00:22:00,720 --> 00:22:06,760
specific uses that needed to get explored very 
early on, and that made it a slightly different  

243
00:22:06,760 --> 00:22:12,920
process for me. In terms of things that didn't 
work though, I think just trying to work on the  

244
00:22:12,920 --> 00:22:18,920
level of detail within the illustration and type 
so that it could shrink down, because we knew...  

245
00:22:18,920 --> 00:22:25,240
One of the primo examples of the logo being 
used was on that podcast avatar, and some of the  

246
00:22:25,240 --> 00:22:31,840
versions felt a little bit too detailed to shrink 
down that much. Trying to get the balance of that,  

247
00:22:31,840 --> 00:22:37,720
having the illustrations feel illustrative and 
whole, but not when they scaled up, to feel too  

248
00:22:37,720 --> 00:22:46,120
simple like we just pulled it from a icon library. 
I think that was an interesting challenge.

249
00:22:46,120 --> 00:22:51,360
One of the impetuses for changing my logo, 
for motivating me, is my wife's a designer,  

250
00:22:51,360 --> 00:22:56,960
as you know. She's got strong opinions about 
my logo, and she always was making fun of  

251
00:22:56,960 --> 00:23:00,720
my logo saying it looked like a clip art 
fireplace that anyone just could just plug  

252
00:23:01,480 --> 00:23:04,280
and play. She's always like, "Oh, that's 
so bad. You got to change it." That was  

253
00:23:04,280 --> 00:23:08,040
one of the motivators. I think I might have 
shared that when we started working together.

254
00:23:08,040 --> 00:23:12,840
Yeah. Also too, I think that really talks to 
what I was saying earlier about making sure that  

255
00:23:12,840 --> 00:23:17,040
everything feels like it was created together 
rather than it feeling like these disparate  

256
00:23:17,040 --> 00:23:24,040
elements, because I think you can have an icon 
or logo that is quite simple as long as the rest  

257
00:23:24,040 --> 00:23:30,920
of the brand matches that simplicity. I think, for 
you, the biggest thing was making the illustration  

258
00:23:30,920 --> 00:23:35,880
and the typography just feel like it came from 
the same universe instead of feeling like these  

259
00:23:35,880 --> 00:23:40,560
separate elements. When I first moved to San 
Francisco, I moved to San Francisco from New York,  

260
00:23:40,560 --> 00:23:46,400
and as a New Yorker, I had an apartment with 
a full kitchen that never got used. I just ate  

261
00:23:46,400 --> 00:23:51,000
at restaurants and did takeout for the seven 
years or whatever that I lived in New York. 

262
00:23:51,000 --> 00:23:56,560
Learning to cook, at first, when you learn how 
to cook, it's like you're making a pot full of  

263
00:23:56,560 --> 00:24:02,080
ingredients and none of the ingredients are 
actually working together. But then the more  

264
00:24:02,080 --> 00:24:06,920
you do it and the more you understand how these 
things are meant to blend and cook at different  

265
00:24:06,920 --> 00:24:14,400
temperatures at different times, you start having 
this cohesive dish rather than hot ham water. You  

266
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:19,400
know what I mean? I feel like a lot of clients 
come to me and they have hot ham water when it  

267
00:24:19,400 --> 00:24:25,400
comes to their brand. It's just about turning 
that into a soup, something that feels real.

268
00:24:25,400 --> 00:24:30,520
I want to take a quick tangent. Most people 
listening to this podcast are not designers.  

269
00:24:30,520 --> 00:24:38,680
They're product managers, founders, engineers, 
and folks building product. I've always wanted  

270
00:24:38,680 --> 00:24:43,880
to see the world through the eyes of a designer, 
because there's so much I don't see and there's so  

271
00:24:43,880 --> 00:24:49,520
much that affects how I think about something that 
I don't understand when I look at a logo, and so I  

272
00:24:49,520 --> 00:24:54,080
thought it might be helpful just to spend a little 
time helping people see a designer a little bit.  

273
00:24:54,080 --> 00:25:00,000
Let me just ask you this question. When people 
look at a logo or a brand, what are just elements  

274
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:06,640
that make it what it is, that make you feel the 
thing you want to feel that we may not recognize?

275
00:25:06,640 --> 00:25:14,800
I think most people are better at understanding 
the feelings and sensations that typography and  

276
00:25:14,800 --> 00:25:22,440
logos give us than they give themselves credit 
for, because what we are as people are endless  

277
00:25:22,440 --> 00:25:27,600
absorbers of patterns, and information, and 
all this kind of stuff as we move throughout  

278
00:25:27,600 --> 00:25:33,840
the world. We don't take time to sit and digest 
it, but it's still coming in and getting logged.  

279
00:25:34,480 --> 00:25:40,040
That's why if you see something funky in the 
world, you're like, "That's weird. I don't like  

280
00:25:40,040 --> 00:25:45,640
that. I don't know why I don't like it, but I know 
I don't like it." I think even as a non-designer,  

281
00:25:45,640 --> 00:25:52,400
you can see that in typography. The whole 
being able to recognize patterns thing,  

282
00:25:52,400 --> 00:26:00,960
I talked about this a bit at config, it's like 
it's a safety thing. Looking into the world, your  

283
00:26:00,960 --> 00:26:07,280
eyes can spot that thing that's a little bit off, 
and that thing that's off feels not safe to you. 

284
00:26:07,960 --> 00:26:13,600
It's thinking about when we look at a meal and 
there's a thing on the plate that looks like it's  

285
00:26:13,600 --> 00:26:18,080
moldy or something like that. You understand 
that doesn't look right to me, this doesn't  

286
00:26:18,080 --> 00:26:24,840
smell right to me. Your body knows it before 
your brain knows it. Even as a non-designer,  

287
00:26:24,840 --> 00:26:29,680
I think you can look at examples of logos 
where something's not quite right and be like,  

288
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:34,960
"Something's not right here, I just don't know 
how to name it." But I think a good exercise is  

289
00:26:34,960 --> 00:26:40,480
just looking at fonts that are available in 
the world and asking yourself, "What feeling  

290
00:26:40,480 --> 00:26:46,560
does this give me?" and just write them down. It 
doesn't matter, just give yourself permission to  

291
00:26:46,560 --> 00:26:51,920
say whatever is happening in your mind, the first 
thing. Don't overanalyze it. Just look at it and  

292
00:26:51,920 --> 00:27:00,320
be like, "That feels calm to me. That feels 
exciting to me. That feels whatever to me." 

293
00:27:00,320 --> 00:27:04,880
The more you do that, the more you 
can start seeing similarities in the  

294
00:27:04,880 --> 00:27:09,080
ones that feel exciting, and the ones that 
feel calm, and the ones that feel whatever,  

295
00:27:09,080 --> 00:27:18,000
and then get into analyze mode of, "Oh, these 10 
things that I said feel calm are a lighter weight,  

296
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:26,560
have more generous spacing, have rounded edges, 
have rounder bowls to the letter forms." You just  

297
00:27:26,560 --> 00:27:32,360
start seeing commonalities between the 
things. It's just about seeing them all  

298
00:27:32,360 --> 00:27:38,080
together to understand what those similarities 
are. I think anybody can do that. I mean,  

299
00:27:38,080 --> 00:27:43,880
you're not going to have the language of the 
leg of the R and the tittle of the I. Don't  

300
00:27:43,880 --> 00:27:50,040
worry about that. You don't have to know 
typography language to think about it, but  

301
00:27:50,040 --> 00:27:57,040
anybody's capable of doing that. It can be really 
fun to just stop and ask yourself and notice.

302
00:27:58,240 --> 00:28:03,560
This is great. I want to go actually a little 
deeper. What I'm hearing is look at something,  

303
00:28:03,560 --> 00:28:07,480
tap into the feeling you feel when you look 
at it, actually pay attention to it because  

304
00:28:07,480 --> 00:28:13,680
there's wisdom in that. The specific things that 
you pointed out that impact that feeling are,  

305
00:28:13,680 --> 00:28:19,840
you mentioned, spacing between the letters, 
the edges. I imagine there's just the color  

306
00:28:19,840 --> 00:28:26,080
of it. What other specific elements impact the 
way someone feels when they look at a logo?

307
00:28:26,080 --> 00:28:33,760
There's the width of the letter, so if it's really 
narrow versus really wide. I always think about  

308
00:28:33,760 --> 00:28:39,240
the width, the weight, [inaudible 00:28:35] 
facing, sort of detailed treatment of things,  

309
00:28:39,240 --> 00:28:45,840
whether things are very hard and jagged or 
soft and how soft it is. Sometimes we just  

310
00:28:45,840 --> 00:28:53,600
add a tiny bit of softness so that it just feels 
printed. You can take a typeface like Helvetica,  

311
00:28:54,360 --> 00:29:00,480
just the one everybody knows. But if you take 
Helvetica and just ever so slightly round the  

312
00:29:00,480 --> 00:29:06,200
edges just a little bit, all of a sudden, you 
have this typeface that feels more vintage,  

313
00:29:06,200 --> 00:29:10,760
or softer, or whatever, because we're 
perceiving it, we would perceive it  

314
00:29:10,760 --> 00:29:18,560
if it were printed on paper versus perceiving 
it as this hard geometric piece of technology  

315
00:29:18,560 --> 00:29:23,200
that we're viewing. You know what I mean?
I know that it's because when you look at stuff  

316
00:29:23,200 --> 00:29:28,440
printed on a page, it bleeds into the paper a 
little bit, which means that that softness reminds  

317
00:29:28,440 --> 00:29:35,400
us in our bodies of a thing that we've seen that 
was printed. It's cool to sort of walk back your  

318
00:29:35,400 --> 00:29:40,560
feelings also. You'll look at something and go, 
"That feels like this," and then ask yourself why  

319
00:29:40,560 --> 00:29:47,760
does it feel like that. It might be because you 
saw it on a flyer for a band when you were 22,  

320
00:29:47,760 --> 00:29:53,320
and it brought out that feeling in you of 
what it felt like to be 22 at that thing.  

321
00:29:53,320 --> 00:29:59,320
That's a very specific feeling to you, but 
it can inform your decisions about design,  

322
00:29:59,320 --> 00:30:03,320
because you can be like, "Oh, I'm not that 
much of a special snowflake." Other people  

323
00:30:03,320 --> 00:30:07,920
might have that same reaction but have different 
experiences that are adjacent to that reaction. 

324
00:30:08,800 --> 00:30:15,120
It's cool because you are reverse-justifying 
decisions. I think that's a really fun exercise  

325
00:30:15,120 --> 00:30:25,440
to do, is to Song Exploder your intuition. 
You make a decision intuitively or look at  

326
00:30:25,440 --> 00:30:31,840
something and intuit what you feel from 
it, and then really try to dive in,  

327
00:30:31,840 --> 00:30:37,360
"Why do I feel that way? What could this have 
reminded me of that made me feel that way?"  

328
00:30:37,360 --> 00:30:41,560
You have to be just so forgiving and loose with 
yourself as you do it because then you'll get  

329
00:30:41,560 --> 00:30:49,800
into some really weird stuff, and that's really 
great inspiration juice for picking other things.

330
00:30:50,920 --> 00:30:55,480
I love the exercise that you gave. The one you 
gave earlier is look at a bunch of fonts, look  

331
00:30:55,480 --> 00:30:58,767
at your font folder. Is that a place to go, just 
open up your font folder and just go through them?

332
00:30:58,767 --> 00:31:04,120
Totally. Look at your font folder, or go to 
MyFonts, or a place where there's a ton of fonts,  

333
00:31:04,120 --> 00:31:09,480
and just search for something. Search for 
sans serif or whatever. Search for a really  

334
00:31:09,480 --> 00:31:18,880
basic category of fonts. Serif, sans serif, 
script, whatever, the top level edge of stuff,  

335
00:31:18,880 --> 00:31:23,080
and then just page through, page through, page 
through. Screenshot stuff that you like and make  

336
00:31:23,080 --> 00:31:28,120
a folder full of screenshots, and then you can 
take those screenshots and start categorizing  

337
00:31:28,120 --> 00:31:31,320
them. "Oh, this one feels feminine. This one 
feels masculine, this one feels aggressive.  

338
00:31:31,320 --> 00:31:36,760
This one feels whatever." Just take some 
notes on it. Then, you ask yourself, "Well,  

339
00:31:36,760 --> 00:31:40,280
why did I feel that way?" You're like, "Oh, well, 
this feels feminine because it reminds me of  

340
00:31:40,280 --> 00:31:48,400
wedding invitations," and wedding invitations feel 
inherently bridey versus groomy. All of a sudden,  

341
00:31:48,400 --> 00:31:53,560
you're like, "Okay. Well, now I know that 
if I'm going to use a script for something,  

342
00:31:53,560 --> 00:32:01,720
this zone of script feels very wedding, so maybe 
I avoid that for this brand that's actually a  

343
00:32:01,720 --> 00:32:08,960
cutting edge food packaging company or whatever 
because it feels too aligned with that industry." 

344
00:32:10,120 --> 00:32:16,800
Stereotypes are real and trends are real, 
and what can sometimes happen is some  

345
00:32:16,800 --> 00:32:23,360
industry usurps an entire style for a period 
of time. If you use anything within that style,  

346
00:32:23,360 --> 00:32:29,680
it's like you're aligning yourself to that 
industry. I mean, everybody that does branding,  

347
00:32:29,680 --> 00:32:34,360
one of the things that they do is they analyze 
the competitors of the company. You just look at  

348
00:32:34,360 --> 00:32:40,840
a landscape of what are all the competitors doing, 
what is their visual vibe, and do I lean into that  

349
00:32:40,840 --> 00:32:47,360
or do I avoid that? If I lean into it, then I'm 
immediately getting this... Everyone that looks  

350
00:32:47,360 --> 00:32:53,360
at it understands I'm a FinTech company because I 
look like a FinTech company. If my whole thing is  

351
00:32:53,360 --> 00:32:59,600
I'm trying to be divergent from that, I'm trying 
to show how different I am from the status quo,  

352
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:04,800
then you use it as a reactionary thing of I 
want to do nothing like that and do something  

353
00:33:04,800 --> 00:33:08,720
really different so people understand 
this isn't just another FinTech company.

354
00:33:08,720 --> 00:33:11,200
Yeah. I'm thinking green. The color green has to  

355
00:33:11,200 --> 00:33:13,800
be a part of the logo if you 
want to be a FinTech company.

356
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:16,960
Yeah, exactly. If you're trying to 
be weird, then you're like teal.

357
00:33:19,800 --> 00:33:24,440
On this topic of seeing a designer, is there 
any other tip, just before we move on to a  

358
00:33:24,440 --> 00:33:30,760
different topic, of just how someone could 
learn to see a designer a little bit more?

359
00:33:30,760 --> 00:33:36,200
Yeah. Another thing to notice, because 
I'm assuming you're... Product people,  

360
00:33:36,200 --> 00:33:40,200
I feel like a lot of product people end up 
having some engineering background, whether  

361
00:33:40,200 --> 00:33:44,680
or not they're engineers themselves. They have to 
interface with the engineers and they build stuff,  

362
00:33:44,680 --> 00:33:50,880
and so they come at it from a data standpoint. 
I can always tell when there's an engineer that  

363
00:33:50,880 --> 00:33:55,000
has suddenly got taken an interest in 
type design and is now a type designer,  

364
00:33:55,000 --> 00:34:02,360
because everything is very, very regular. You can 
draw a grid on top of everything and the lines  

365
00:34:02,360 --> 00:34:08,280
all line up perfectly. You see lots of reverse 
justification of that when people are making logos  

366
00:34:08,280 --> 00:34:14,560
and they have a more engineering background. The 
thing to notice, that is interesting within type,  

367
00:34:14,560 --> 00:34:19,480
is that, yes, you're absolutely following 
rules, but you're breaking those rules  

368
00:34:19,480 --> 00:34:26,800
quite often to correct for optical tricks.
If you look at a geometric sans serif, for  

369
00:34:26,800 --> 00:34:31,120
instance, that's like a category of sans serifs, 
and they're meant to have a lot of really strong  

370
00:34:31,120 --> 00:34:37,320
geometry, be very regular, like most of the sans 
that you think of that you're like, "I'm in love  

371
00:34:37,320 --> 00:34:42,840
with this over the last 10 years," like geometric 
sanses. But when you really start to examine them,  

372
00:34:42,840 --> 00:34:47,480
you notice that there's all these little 
things that people are doing to make them  

373
00:34:47,480 --> 00:34:53,840
look perfectly geometric even though they are 
not mathematically perfectly geometric. That's  

374
00:34:53,840 --> 00:34:57,280
another thing that you can do, whether you're 
doing it in Figma or doing it somewhere else,  

375
00:34:57,280 --> 00:35:04,520
is just type out a couple of lowercase letters. 
Lowercase specifically are really good for  

376
00:35:04,520 --> 00:35:09,400
analyzing this because they're smaller than the 
uppercase letters. You usually have to accommodate  

377
00:35:09,400 --> 00:35:16,960
for the weight a little bit differently. You'll 
notice that when strokes combine, so say I have an  

378
00:35:16,960 --> 00:35:23,920
A and I'm combining the lower bowl of the A, I'm 
going to get a little thinner as I come into that. 

379
00:35:23,920 --> 00:35:30,920
Or say I have a two-storey A, so a two-storey 
A is the one that's like this and then a bowl,  

380
00:35:30,920 --> 00:35:38,200
you might notice that this vertical of the A 
there, the bowl actually eats into that stroke  

381
00:35:38,200 --> 00:35:46,720
a little bit to erase a little bit of that added 
weight that would've been perceived optically had  

382
00:35:46,720 --> 00:35:53,360
you kept everything perfectly regular. It's 
weird because you end up creating something  

383
00:35:53,360 --> 00:35:57,480
that's perfect and then have to make it not 
perfect in order to make it be perceived as  

384
00:35:57,480 --> 00:36:05,360
perfect. That's another just fun thing to start 
noticing. You notice it a lot more on typefaces  

385
00:36:05,360 --> 00:36:10,640
and typography that is heavier in weight, because 
when things are heavier weight, you're constantly  

386
00:36:10,640 --> 00:36:16,840
managing these really inky moments where things 
join together and you have to subtract a bunch of  

387
00:36:16,840 --> 00:36:22,760
weight from that so that it doesn't get perceived 
as this dark mark where the letter is happening. 

388
00:36:22,760 --> 00:36:31,000
I think about lowercase Rs and lowercase Ns, 
where the shoulder of the N or the R comes out,  

389
00:36:31,000 --> 00:36:36,280
sometimes the top of the R is actually 
narrower at the top than it is on the bottom,  

390
00:36:36,280 --> 00:36:41,200
and that's to try to subtract some of that 
weight in there where that join happens. Anyway,  

391
00:36:41,200 --> 00:36:46,000
that's just a fun thing to notice that you 
have to do that. Once you start seeing it,  

392
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:53,720
you start seeing where it happens more often, 
