00:50:49,280 --> 00:50:55,400
owns everything as you are moving along. It's 
all sort of work for hire, but the idea being  

548
00:50:55,400 --> 00:51:01,280
that it's a buyout of everything that is being 
made. What that means is that when a branding  

549
00:51:01,280 --> 00:51:06,760
agency is pricing stuff for you, they're 
taking the buyout rights and baking it into  

550
00:51:06,760 --> 00:51:13,200
every round of work so that every round gets more 
expensive because you are owning all of the work. 

551
00:51:14,200 --> 00:51:18,680
What I do is I treat it much more like a 
commercial lettering project where I say,  

552
00:51:18,680 --> 00:51:22,880
"You have to own the rights to this eventually, 
but hey, let's break that out and let's keep the  

553
00:51:22,880 --> 00:51:29,920
creative process lighter and less expensive so 
then we have more room to explore. So then if  

554
00:51:29,920 --> 00:51:34,600
some stakeholder comes in last minute and blows 
everything else up and we need to start over,  

555
00:51:34,600 --> 00:51:39,600
you haven't already paid to own everything that 
we've created, you just pay to own the thing  

556
00:51:39,600 --> 00:51:45,520
that we create in the end that gets chosen." 
I really like the idea of keeping the creation  

557
00:51:45,520 --> 00:51:52,240
process more flexible and to try to scale to 
what people need versus having a really rigid  

558
00:51:52,240 --> 00:51:57,360
way of approaching everything. Sometimes people 
will bring me on really early in the process,  

559
00:51:57,360 --> 00:52:02,680
where if they have an internal team or if they're 
working with an external agency or something,  

560
00:52:02,680 --> 00:52:07,000
they want me there from the get out.
Some people are like, "We have no money  

561
00:52:07,000 --> 00:52:11,840
and we are going to try to do this as much as we 
can inside of our business, but then can we hire  

562
00:52:11,840 --> 00:52:16,680
you at the end to make it look good? If we can 
get everybody bought in and get it 80% of the way  

563
00:52:16,680 --> 00:52:22,740
there." Depending on what people's budgets are, I 
have different ways of working, or just depending  

564
00:52:22,740 --> 00:52:26,520
on what their needs are. Because my whole thing 
too is I don't want to step on anybody's toes,  

565
00:52:27,080 --> 00:52:32,640
because sometimes companies have these really 
amazing designers that are working in-house, and  

566
00:52:32,640 --> 00:52:37,720
it sucks as a designer who started at a company 
and thinks that you might be able to get a chance  

567
00:52:37,720 --> 00:52:43,320
to work on what is considered the most important 
asset in terms of the brand and they just farm it  

568
00:52:43,320 --> 00:52:49,360
out to someone else instead of letting you touch 
it. To me, that's a recipe for anything that I  

569
00:52:49,360 --> 00:52:54,880
create to be immediately killed, because someone 
inside is going to be like, "It's time to shine,"  

570
00:52:54,880 --> 00:53:00,280
and then they're just going to kill all my work.
I'm always like, "How do we collaborate? How do I  

571
00:53:00,280 --> 00:53:05,480
make it so that I'm an asset to you? Not that I'm 
trying to step on your toes, not that I'm trying  

572
00:53:05,480 --> 00:53:10,000
to take over what's the cool juicy work from 
the people who inside that are really excited  

573
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:15,280
to do it." I just want them to feel as bought in 
as I can be. But yeah, it becomes interesting.  

574
00:53:16,920 --> 00:53:21,800
I feel like I get told by branding people that 
I'm too inexpensive because they're like, "Oh,  

575
00:53:21,800 --> 00:53:26,520
for what you do, it should be 60 or $70,000 at a 
minimum to do all this kind of stuff." I'm like,  

576
00:53:26,520 --> 00:53:31,840
I feel like the majority of the projects 
that I do end up being between 25 and 35,  

577
00:53:31,840 --> 00:53:39,800
but depending on how you bring me in, it can be 
less if it's just as a consultant. It's not out  

578
00:53:39,800 --> 00:53:45,160
of the realm of possibilities to hire a proper 
crazy expert at stuff. It's not like you're  

579
00:53:45,160 --> 00:53:50,920
thinking about sinking half a million dollars into 
the brand. That's a very different experience.

580
00:53:50,920 --> 00:53:55,680
Awesome. Thank you for sharing that. Before we 
get into other stuff that you do, because like  

581
00:53:55,680 --> 00:54:00,640
you said at the top, there are many other things 
you do outside of this specific time of work,  

582
00:54:00,640 --> 00:54:05,400
is there anything else you think might be helpful 
or important for people to know about working with  

583
00:54:05,400 --> 00:54:11,200
you on a logo refresh or just thinking about 
logos and this whole space we talked about?

584
00:54:11,200 --> 00:54:17,600
The best thing is just seeing what's there and 
really being able to understand what's not working  

585
00:54:17,600 --> 00:54:26,200
about it and what your goals are. Like I said with 
that reverse justification of intuition, I think  

586
00:54:26,200 --> 00:54:33,080
if you know that the logo is not quite where you 
want it to be, just spend a couple days asking  

587
00:54:33,080 --> 00:54:38,480
yourself why. "What is the thing about this that 
bothers me?" Don't get specific. Don't be like,  

588
00:54:38,480 --> 00:54:43,400
"The way the R is," or whatever. Maybe that's the 
thing that we talk about down the line, but always  

589
00:54:43,400 --> 00:54:49,880
think big picture before you think minutiae, 
because sometimes people think that... They'll  

590
00:54:49,880 --> 00:54:55,600
throw a bunch of minutiae stuff at me, but it's 
because they haven't really stopped to think about  

591
00:54:55,600 --> 00:55:00,960
what is the overall thing that's bothering them.
You just never get there if you're always trying  

592
00:55:00,960 --> 00:55:06,720
to address detail before you address the big 
picture stuff. You have to just always start  

593
00:55:06,720 --> 00:55:12,160
super top level, and really ask yourself very 
broad questions about why you think it's not  

594
00:55:12,160 --> 00:55:19,120
working, and then go tighter, and tighter, and 
tighter, and be like... It really could be like,  

595
00:55:19,120 --> 00:55:24,280
"This C has always bothered me," and then we can 
get real specific about that when I'm doing the  

596
00:55:24,280 --> 00:55:29,800
refresh. But I think I also need to understand 
the overall reason why we're doing this,  

597
00:55:29,800 --> 00:55:35,720
not just the little bugaboo that bothers you 
specifically but might not bother anybody else.

598
00:55:35,720 --> 00:55:40,600
Yeah. When I was thinking about this, 
it feels like my whole feeling was this  

599
00:55:40,600 --> 00:55:43,360
could be better. That's all it was 
for me initially, is just like I  

600
00:55:43,360 --> 00:55:47,120
feel like it could be a lot better. I 
imagine that's enough for some people,  

601
00:55:47,120 --> 00:55:49,720
just like, "I think this could be better," 
and then here's things [inaudible 00:55:50].

602
00:55:49,720 --> 00:55:55,040
Yeah. That's definitely enough for some people, 
because I think sometimes... I think you,  

603
00:55:55,040 --> 00:56:02,200
specifically, had a very clear vibe going on 
with all of your brand stuff. Some people,  

604
00:56:02,200 --> 00:56:09,080
it's totally like a mishmash grab bag of random 
trends and there's no real voice that's coming  

605
00:56:09,080 --> 00:56:14,320
through. But I feel like you've been doing this 
for a while, and when you see everything together,  

606
00:56:14,320 --> 00:56:21,320
there's definitely a very clear vision 
and vibe that you get from everything.  

607
00:56:21,320 --> 00:56:27,000
I always tell people that having terrible 
vision can be your best asset when it comes  

608
00:56:27,000 --> 00:56:33,040
to logo and brand, because it allows you...
Just take your glasses off if you have terrible  

609
00:56:33,040 --> 00:56:39,360
vision, and look at it, and get the feeling when 
you can't see the detail. You have to be looking  

610
00:56:39,360 --> 00:56:46,760
at it with blurred eyes. What is the overall 
look of this thing? Just trying to get as broad  

611
00:56:46,760 --> 00:56:52,960
and noodly as you can with it instead of it 
being about those really specific one by one  

612
00:56:52,960 --> 00:56:58,760
stuff. I think when you blur your eyes on your 
brand, there was a really clear cohesiveness to  

613
00:56:58,760 --> 00:57:07,040
it already. It was just about massaging it into 
a more consistent professional-looking place.

614
00:57:07,040 --> 00:57:11,880
Well, I can't look at the old logo anymore now 
