01:09:42,560 --> 01:09:48,160
and was also... I feel like I'm reading a lot 
of books about being an artist more so than  

752
01:09:48,160 --> 01:09:55,520
being a designer. That book, I found really 
interesting, just hearing her story of moving  

753
01:09:55,520 --> 01:10:01,200
to New York and having nothing. Just trying to 
be an artist, and make art, and having that be  

754
01:10:01,200 --> 01:10:06,520
the thing that drove everything that she 
and Robert Mapplethorpe did. I don't know,  

755
01:10:06,520 --> 01:10:14,440
I just feel like I'm looking for ways to get out 
of my very business-driven sensibilities around  

756
01:10:14,440 --> 01:10:20,720
art making and get into a space that's more 
loose, and free, and driven by passions and  

757
01:10:20,720 --> 01:10:30,040
feelings more so than necessarily career-based 
milestones and things like that. This is a wild  

758
01:10:30,040 --> 01:10:36,720
card one too. I just finished The Emperor of All 
Maladies. I'm just a big fan of reading things  

759
01:10:36,720 --> 01:10:40,800
about human biology and things like that and found 
it totally fascinating, so do read that one too.

760
01:10:40,800 --> 01:10:43,880
I can't help but ask, how do you 
have time to read, raise children,  

761
01:10:43,880 --> 01:10:49,760
work on so many projects, have a 
run a store? What is your secret?

762
01:10:50,320 --> 01:10:53,760
Well, you get pretty ruthless about 
your schedule when you're a parent,  

763
01:10:53,760 --> 01:11:01,000
where when you're at the office, you are just 
heads in working, and so I think just trying  

764
01:11:01,000 --> 01:11:07,200
to stay as focused as possible in that way. I do 
this thing where I bounce back and forth between  

765
01:11:07,200 --> 01:11:14,040
projects a lot as I'm losing steam, and so 
having multiple things to work on keeps me  

766
01:11:14,040 --> 01:11:20,600
motivated to keep working. I think it's kind of 
an ADHD thing, where I will start my day one way  

767
01:11:20,600 --> 01:11:24,040
and then as soon as I start losing steam, 
I switch to a different thing, lose steam,  

768
01:11:24,040 --> 01:11:29,000
switch to a different thing, lose steam, switch 
to a different thing. Rather than taking breaks,  

769
01:11:29,000 --> 01:11:33,560
I just take a break by working on something 
that feels fresh. That can be super helpful.

770
01:11:33,560 --> 01:11:35,120
That's an awesome tip.

771
01:11:35,120 --> 01:11:39,800
Yeah. I mean, it's incredible. I also would 
tell people when I had first started out,  

772
01:11:39,800 --> 01:11:44,360
I had a full-time job and then was doing freelance 
in the evenings. People were like, "How do you not  

773
01:11:44,360 --> 01:11:50,320
get burnt out, whatever?" It's because my day job 
was so different from my night job that it felt  

774
01:11:50,320 --> 01:11:55,240
like I was doing two separate eight-hour shifts 
instead of one continual sixteen-hour shift.  

775
01:11:56,120 --> 01:11:59,960
I think that's something to sort of think 
about, is that there's always going to be  

776
01:11:59,960 --> 01:12:04,040
things that need to get done as a part of 
your work or things that you're interested  

777
01:12:04,040 --> 01:12:09,200
in and passionate about. Just having enough 
diversity in what that means is going to allow  

778
01:12:09,200 --> 01:12:15,760
you to maintain enthusiasm for doing all those 
different things for much longer. Actually,  

779
01:12:16,280 --> 01:12:23,880
the more homogenous your life and career and 
job is, the faster you're going to burn out,  

780
01:12:23,880 --> 01:12:27,480
so just making sure that you have enough 
variety and all the things that you do.

781
01:12:27,480 --> 01:12:30,880
That was an awesome tip. I'm glad I 
